        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2662148674" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16720911528016088263">This is by far the most comprehensive book on cosmology I&apos;ve ever read. What&apos;s more, it&apos;s probably the most effective and we&apos;ll written one as well. Granted, how I responded to the book is influenced by my own science background, but I 100% recommend this to others interested in learning about the fundamental nature of reality.<br/><br/>I loved hearing about various forms of research that have since been confirmed experimentally (i.e. gravitational waves and the higgs boson). I also appreciated how this c</span>
  <span id="freeText16720911528016088263" style="display:none">This is by far the most comprehensive book on cosmology I've ever read. What's more, it's probably the most effective and we'll written one as well. Granted, how I responded to the book is influenced by my own science background, but I 100% recommend this to others interested in learning about the fundamental nature of reality.<br /><br />I loved hearing about various forms of research that have since been confirmed experimentally (i.e. gravitational waves and the higgs boson). I also appreciated how this contrasted with the NOVA documentary. <br /><br />This was just as engaging and even more informative. The only other book, by Brian Greene, that I've read is his 2014 book <i>The Hidden Reality</i>. I never picked up this book, which is the perfect introduction to cosmology, because I had seen the Nova documentary, and I did not think it was necessary to read the book. As it stands, reading this nearly a decade after I watch that, I leave this with the better understanding than I had before.<br /><br />There were questions I had after I watched that documentary, especially to do with the nature of time. How I interpreted that documentary heavily influenced how I saw the nature of reality. I think the only other thing that really had a profound effect on me was interstellar's use of time dilation, but even my love of that stemmed from this documentary. Nevertheless, I moved forward comfortable with my own uncomfortable incomplete understanding of the nature of reality. Granted, there were things I inferred from what Greene was trying to say in the documentary, but it was made much more explicit in this book.<br /><br />Had I read this book sooner, a lot of my questions would have been clarified much sooner. The books I've read before this, would have made more sense had I started with this first. The big thing that I'm referring to here is this concept of essentially the block universe. This idea that time isn't something that comes with existence and changes it is all points in time to pass in the future all being as real as the perceived now. <br /><br />However this was only at the beginning of the book. He dug so much deeper into the nature of reality, clarifying concepts that I have always made confused about, and introducing me to a few new ones. To summarize, I love this book, obviously. Read it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16720911528016088263" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


